<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I read most of it and found much of the replies on the various sights misinterpreted the purpose of the guide.  Maybe I'm misinterpreting the purpose of your post.<P>The thing I see is that you are trying to work up a strategy for changing main tanks when the first one is about to die.  Is this correct?<P>Anyway, I think the bubble diagram is nice.  I would suggest a thing or two.<P>First, on uber encounters most rangers will use their trueshot discipline.  This means that they will be out of the bubble at max distance shooting arrows.  The only limiting factor so far on this is that if the mob is in the wall the shots will rarely take.  What has to happen is the ranger has to move closer to the mob and stand next to the wall where the mob is pushed into and shoot arrows.  They will make more shots but not a whole lot more.<P>If you can keep the mobs position in the right place that is a big boon on many encounters of this size.  Keeping the mobs out of the walls will help the ranger greatly with trueshot.  Many rangers can really contribute.<P>Here's what I think you are missing for ranger agro management on uber encounters.<P>1)  Use trueshot to start the fight.  When you use this use it to the end of the discipline or until you run out of arrows.  If you fail to make enough for the fight, shame on you.  Use your eagle eye type spells to help you increase your probability to hit.  Slow bows with big damage/delay will do more damage and sometimes this is better then small damage low delay with trueshot.<P>2)  After trueshot has expired use Jolt or cinder jolt on the mob.<P>3)  After you jolt, go in and waste 80% of your mana on Firestrike and Calefaction.  These usually hit most uber mobs.  Do Calefaction and then use firestrike till Calefaction recycles.  Then repeat.  It would be best to jolt every so often.  Even a resisted jolt will lower your agro.<P>4)  When you have used 80% of your mana then go in and melee.  Get rid of your procing epic and replace it with something nearly equivalent that does not proc.  I use a priceless warhammer from ST.  It allows me to keep up my damage.<P>5)  Stay behind the mob with the rogues and the monks.  That's your position.  You have already built a bunch of agro from trueshot and your spells so you need to use that last 20% of mana on jolt.  Keep using it every so often.<P>In general I would suggest that ALL melee that are not the main tank turn off their attack every 10-15 seconds and turn it on 5 seconds after that, except the person that is going to be the next main tank.  They need to not take agro from the mob but they need to build agro higher then anyone else.<P>Here is what typically happens on fight where agro must be transferred form the MT to the next in line.  The MT dies (most of the time) and then the mob turns to the other warriors and slaughters them before the next one can go defensive and gain agro.  So, you see the MT die and then boom boom boom, all the other tanks go too.  The next players to go are the rogues and the wizards.<P>The goal is to find a way to allow the next MT in sequence to transfer successfully without having all the other tanks killed during the transfer.  When this happens the fight is over for the most part.<P>Rezzing in during a fight is important too.  Doing so is important on some fights.  When this occurs someone must rebuff the tanks again so they can take over again if necessary.  This means they must have their taunt ability increased.<P>I as a ranger will always try to remember to stand back once in a while and cast CoP and CoE on the newly rez'd warrior.  If I am playing my 60 cleric I will also try to Aego them.  It is silly to send in an unbuffed warrior.<P>During any fight I as a ranger will never fight in front of the mob.  When the mob enrages it is important to turn off your attack or at least be behind the mob so enrage doesn't get you.  Rampage is the same.  You have to be aware of which mobs will do this.  Get into a position where you will not get hit by hit.<P>Even rangers are worth healing.  Keep players above 50% health.  This is a no-brianer.  If the mob decides you are low health you are dead.  So keep them healed.  This isn't hard to do.  If you are a cleric instruct your druids to heal as much as possible those getting close to less then 1/2 life.  This will greatly help reduce mob bouncing.<P>I have seen encounters were the uber mob is pulled and there are adds.  In this case there's a main team that focuses on having the main tank take the blows while everyone else focuses on killing the adds.  Last time I saw this was with the statue of rallos zek.  Two armorers were pulled in addition to this and the guild that did this mob didn't flinch.  The main tank, an ogre warrior level 60, just tanked the statue while the rest of the guild focused on the armorers.  Then when the fight was in progress with everyone going full force on the statue everyone remember to periodically turn off their attack.
</FONT>
